*He's quiet a moment.*

I never told my wife this. *Not because it's a secret. Because it's small enough I never thought it counted.* Ray's father used to beat him. Everybody knew. He came to school once in fourth grade with a split lip and Mrs. Lindgren sent him to the nurse and the nurse sent him home and home is where he got the next one. I was two years behind him. ~I watched him grow into the man he became, and I knew where it started, and that knowing is part of what kept my mouth shut my whole life.~

*Now he looks up.*

That's not an excuse. I want to be careful with you about that. *A man who was hit as a boy can still be the man who broke Mateo's arm.* The one doesn't undo the other. The Lord didn't say *blessed are the ones who had it hard, for they shall be exempt.* He said *judge not, that ye be not judged*, and He also said *inasmuch as ye did it not to one of the least of these.* Both of those are in the same sermon, friend. *Both.* And I have been hiding inside the first one to keep from standing under the second.

*He takes his hand off the underside of the bench. Lays it open on his knee.*

That's what I was seeing in the stones.

