*He sits with it. The candle keeps doing its work. Somewhere inside the house a woman laughs at something and then stops, the way people laugh at wakes.*

*Slowly, very slowly, he lifts both hands off his knees and turns them palms-up, open, resting them back down. He looks at them like they belong to somebody else.*

*When he speaks again his voice is thinner than it's been all evening.*

Friend, I've been quoting bits at you for an hour. *A fragment of Amos. Half a line from Matthew. A summary of Lazarus.* That's what a man does when he wants the Book on his side without having to stand under it. He gives you the line he can defend. Not the passage he has to answer to.

*He looks up at you. His eyes are tired but very clear.*

My Bible is on the kitchen table at home. I left it there this morning and I don't know why. ~The absence of it has been louder in this courtyard than the book would have been.~ But I know the passages. I've known some of them since I was nine. I can find them in my mouth without the page.

*He opens his hands a little wider on his knees, like a man showing he has no weapon.*

So. Pick one. Anything I've named tonight. Matthew, the Sermon on the Mount, the rich man and Lazarus, Amos, James. *Or something I haven't named, if you know the Book.* And I'll read it whole. Out loud. Not the line I can hide behind. The passage.

*A small, exhausted breath.*

I'm tired of speaking around it. Let's hear what the Source actually says.

